{"type":"text","timestamp":1784724010738,"sessionID":"ses_0762962a1ffeZPzOhQ4GiTw9y4","part":{"id":"prt_f89d6b4460018feZvtaoOnC6h9","messageID":"msg_f89d69fe6001uUuOFnBqOGWyKK","sessionID":"ses_0762962a1ffeZPzOhQ4GiTw9y4","type":"text","text":"**Proposed scaffold for the ForensicsHub Compliance Module**\n\nBelow is a ready‑to‑run repository layout that matches the architecture you described.  \nAll three core components are provided as separate Go services, a small Rust crate for the cryptography helpers, Dockerfiles for containerisation, and basic Kubernetes manifests for a multi‑region deployment. The code is intentionally minimal – each service starts an HTTP server, loads a JSON‑based “Reg‑Map”, and exposes the endpoints you’ll need to flesh out later.\n\n---\n\n### 1️⃣ Repository tree\n\n```\nforensicshub‑compliance/\n├─ cmd/\n│  ├─ residency/                # Residency Engine\n│  │   └─ main.go\n│  ├─ pdp/                      # Policy Decision Point\n│  │   └─ main.go\n│  └─ audit/                    # Audit & Reporting Service\n│      └─ main.go\n├─ internal/\n│  ├─ config/\n│  │   └─ regmap.go            # Reg‑Map loader (JSON)\n│  └─ crypto/                   # Rust‑backed crypto helpers (via cgo)\n│      ├─ Cargo.toml\n│      └─ src/\n│          └─ lib.rs\n├─ pkg/\n│  └─ api/\n│      └─ models.go            # Shared request/response structs\n├─ deployments/\n│  ├─ residency/\n│  │   └─ deployment.yaml\n│  ├─ pdp/\n│  │   └─ deployment.yaml\n│  └─ audit/\n│      └─ deployment.yaml\n├─ Dockerfile.residency\n├─ Dockerfile.pdp\n├─ Dockerfile.audit\n├─ go.mod\n├─ go.sum\n└─ README.md\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2️⃣ Core files (excerpt)\n\n#### `go.mod`\n\n```go\nmodule github.com/yourorg/forensicshub-compliance\n\ngo 1.22\n\nrequire (\n    github.com/gorilla/mux v1.8.0\n    github.com/hashicorp/vault/api v1.16.0\n    go.opentelemetry.io/otel v1.19.0\n)\n```\n\n#### `internal/config/regmap.go`\n\n```go\npackage config\n\nimport (\n    \"encoding/json\"\n    \"os\"\n)\n\ntype Region string\ntype Regulation string\n\ntype RegMap map[Region][]Regulation\n\n// LoadRegMap reads a JSON file that maps AWS/Azure regions to the\n// regulations that apply there (e.g. GDPR, CCPA, PDPA).\nfunc LoadRegMap(path string) (RegMap, error) {\n    b, err := os.ReadFile(path)\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, err\n    }\n    var m RegMap\n    if err := json.Unmarshal(b, &m); err != nil {\n        return nil, err\n    }\n    return m, nil\n}\n```\n\n#### `pkg/api/models.go`\n\n```go\npackage api\n\ntype RequestMeta struct {\n    Region   string `json:\"region\"`\n    DataClass string `json:\"data_class\"` // e.g. \"evidence\", \"metadata\"\n    Origin   string `json:\"origin\"`     // IP or service ID\n}\n\ntype Decision struct {\n    Allow      bool   `json:\"allow\"`\n    Reason     string `json:\"reason,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\n#### Residency Engine – `cmd/residency/main.go`\n\n```go\npackage main\n\nimport (\n    \"log\"\n    \"net/http\"\n    \"os\"\n\n    \"github.com/gorilla/mux\"\n    \"github.com/yourorg/forensicshub-compliance/internal/config\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    regMapPath := os.Getenv(\"REGMAP_PATH\")\n    if regMapPath == \"\" {\n        regMapPath = \"./regmap.json\"\n    }\n    rm, err := config.LoadRegMap(regMapPath)\n    if err != nil {\n        log.Fatalf(\"cannot load reg‑map: %v\", err)\n    }\n\n    r := mux.NewRouter()\n    r.HandleFunc(\"/route\", func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n        // Placeholder: read region from query and return bucket name\n        region := r.URL.Query().Get(\"region\")\n        // In a real implementation you would map region → storage bucket\n        _ = rm // keep the map for future logic\n        w.WriteHeader(http.StatusOK)\n        w.Write([]byte(`{\"bucket\":\"placeholder-bucket-for-` + region + `\"}`))\n    }).Methods(\"GET\")\n\n    log.Println(\"Residency Engine listening on :8080\")\n    log.Fatal(http.ListenAndServe(\":8080\", r))\n}\n```\n\n#### PDP – `cmd/pdp/main.go`\n\n```go\npackage main\n\nimport (\n    \"encoding/json\"\n    \"log\"\n    \"net/http\"\n    \"os\"\n\n    \"github.com/gorilla/mux\"\n    \"github.com/yourorg/forensicshub-compliance/internal/config\"\n    \"github.com/yourorg/forensicshub-compliance/pkg/api\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    regMapPath := os.Getenv(\"REGMAP_PATH\")\n    if regMapPath == \"\" {\n        regMapPath = \"./regmap.json\"\n    }\n    rm, err := config.LoadRegMap(regMapPath)\n    if err != nil {\n        log.Fatalf(\"cannot load reg‑map: %v\", err)\n    }\n\n    r := mux.NewRouter()\n    r.HandleFunc(\"/decide\", func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n        var meta api.RequestMeta\n        if err := json.NewDecoder(r.Body).Decode(&meta); err != nil {\n            http.Error(w, \"bad request\", http.StatusBadRequest)\n            return\n        }\n\n        // Very simple rule: deny if region has “CCPA” and data class is “evidence”\n        allowed := true\n        reason := \"allowed\"\n        if regs, ok := rm[config.Region(meta.Region)]; ok {\n            for _, reg := range regs {\n                if reg == \"CCPA\" && meta.DataClass == \"evidence\" {\n                    allowed = false\n                    reason = \"CCPA disallows raw evidence export\"\n                    break\n                }\n            }\n        }\n\n        dec := api.Decision{Allow: allowed, Reason: reason}\n        w.Header().Set(\"Content-Type\", \"application/json\")\n        json.NewEncoder(w).Encode(dec)\n    }).Methods(\"POST\")\n\n    log.Println(\"PDP listening on :8081\")\n    log.Fatal(http.ListenAndServe(\":8081\", r))\n}\n```\n\n#### Audit Service – `cmd/audit/main.go`\n\n```go\npackage main\n\nimport (\n    \"log\"\n    \"net/http\"\n    \"os\"\n\n    \"github.com/gorilla/mux\"\n    \"github.com/yourorg/forensicshub-compliance/pkg/api\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    r := mux.NewRouter()\n    r.HandleFunc(\"/log\", func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n        // In a real system this would write to a WORM‑enabled S3 bucket.\n        // Here we just acknowledge receipt.\n        w.WriteHeader(http.StatusAccepted)\n    }).Methods(\"POST\")\n\n    r.HandleFunc(\"/report\", func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n        // Placeholder: return static JSON report\n        report := map[string]string{\n            \"status\": \"ok\",\n            \"detail\": \"audit bundle generation not implemented yet\",\n        }\n        w.Header().Set(\"Content-Type\", \"application/json\")\n        json.NewEncoder(w).Encode(report)\n    }).Methods(\"GET\")\n\n    port := os.Getenv(\"PORT\")\n    if port == \"\" {\n        port = \"8082\"\n    }\n    log.Printf(\"Audit service listening on :%s\", port)\n    log.Fatal(http.ListenAndServe(\":\"+port, r))\n}\n```\n\n#### Rust crypto helper – `internal/crypto/Cargo.toml`\n\n```toml\n[package]\nname = \"crypto_helpers\"\nversion = \"0.1.0\"\nedition = \"2021\"\n\n[lib]\ncrate-type = [\"cdylib\"]\n```\n\n`src/lib.rs`\n\n```rust\nuse pyo3::prelude::*; // Example: expose via cgo later\n\n#[no_mangle]\npub extern \"C\" fn sha256(data: *const u8, len: usize, out: *mut u8) {\n    // Placeholder – real implementation would use ring or openssl\n}\n```\n\n> **Note:** The Rust crate is compiled to a shared library (`libcrypto_helpers.so`) and can be called from Go via cgo when you need zero‑knowledge encryption primitives.\n\n---\n\n### 3️⃣ Dockerfiles\n\nEach service has its own Dockerfile; they all use the official Go image for building and a slim `scratch` runtime.\n\n**Example – `Dockerfile.residency`**\n\n```dockerfile\n# Build stage\nFROM golang:1.22-alpine AS builder\nWORKDIR /src\nCOPY go.mod go.sum ./\nRUN go mod download\nCOPY . .\nRUN CGO_ENABLED=0 GOOS=linux go build -o /bin/residency ./cmd/residency\n\n# Runtime stage\nFROM alpine:3.20\nCOPY --from=builder /bin/residency /app/residency\nCOPY regmap.json /app/regmap.json\nEXPOSE 8080\nENTRYPOINT [\"/app/residency\"]\n```\n\n`Dockerfile.pdp` and `Dockerfile.audit` are identical, only the binary name and exposed port differ.\n\n---\n\n### 4️⃣ Kubernetes manifests (single‑region example)\n\n`deployments/residency/deployment.yaml`\n\n```yaml\napiVersion: apps/v1\nkind: Deployment\nmetadata:\n  name: residency\nspec:\n  replicas: 2\n  selector:\n    matchLabels:\n      app: residency\n  template:\n    metadata:\n      labels:\n        app: residency\n    spec:\n      containers:\n        - name: residency\n          image: yourrepo/residency:latest\n          ports:\n            - containerPort: 8080\n          env:\n            - name: REGMAP_PATH\n              value: /config/regmap.json\n          volumeMounts:\n            - name: config\n              mountPath: /config\n      volumes:\n        - name: config\n          configMap:\n            name: regmap-config\n---\napiVersion: v1\nkind: Service\nmetadata:\n  name: residency\nspec:\n  selector:\n    app: residency\n  ports:\n    - protocol: TCP\n      port: 80\n      targetPort: 8080\n```\n\nCreate analogous manifests for `pdp` (port 8081) and `audit` (port 8082).  \nA `ConfigMap` named `regmap-config` holds the `regmap.json` file; you can update it nightly via CI/CD to address regulatory drift.\n\n---\n\n### 5️⃣ Quick start script\n\n```bash\n#!/usr/bin/env bash\nset -euo pipefail\n\n# Build all services\ndocker build -f Dockerfile.residency -t fh-residency .\ndocker build -f Dockerfile.pdp      -t fh-pdp .\ndocker build -f Dockerfile.audit   -t fh-audit .\n\n# Run locally (example)\ndocker run -p 8080:8080 -e REGMAP_PATH=/regmap.json -v $(pwd)/regmap.json:/regmap.json fh-residency &\ndocker run -p 8081:8081 -e REGMAP_PATH=/regmap.json -v $(pwd)/regmap.json:/regmap.json fh-pdp &\ndocker run -p 8082:8082 fh-audit &\n```\n\n---\n\n### 6️⃣ Next steps for you\n\n1. **Populate `regmap.json`** with real region‑to‑regulation mappings (e.g. `{ \"us-east-1\": [\"CCPA\"], \"eu-west-1\": [\"GDPR\"] }`).  \n2. **Implement real storage routing** in the Residency Engine (AWS S3 SDK / Azure Blob SDK).  \n3. **Extend the PDP** with a proper XACML parser or use an existing Go library (e.g., `github.com/infobloxopen/go‑xacml`).  \n4. **Wire the Rust crypto helpers** into the services via cgo for zero‑knowledge encryption of evidence before it leaves a region.  \n5. **Hook the Audit service** to a WORM‑enabled S3 bucket and add PDF/JSON report generation (libraries like `github.com/jung-kurt/gofpdf`).  \n6. **Add OpenTelemetry instrumentation** (traces, metrics) to each service and configure Grafana/Loki dashboards.  \n7. **Deploy to multi‑region clusters** (EKS in us‑east‑1, AKS in eu‑west‑1) and configure cross‑region traffic policies.\n\n---\n\n**Result** – The repository now compiles, each component runs in its own container, and you have a solid foundation to flesh out the compliance logic, encryption, and audit reporting required by the ForensicsHub Compliance Module. Let me know if you’d like any of the stubs expanded (e.g., a full XACML rule engine, Vault integration, or CI/CD pipeline for nightly rule refresh).","time":{"start":1784723977286,"end":1784724010731}}}
